26
00:00:59,026 --> 00:01:00,994 line:-1
This can help us think
more broadly


27
00:01:00.994 --> 00:01:03.530 line:-1 position:50%
than our own experiences.


28
00:01:03,530 --> 00:01:06,066 line:-1
Diversity axes
can include class; culture;


29
00:01:06,066 --> 00:01:08,535 line:-1
ethnicity; language; education;


30
00:01:08.535 --> 00:01:11.972 line:-1 position:50%
political, philosophical
and religious beliefs;


31
00:01:11.972 --> 00:01:14.908 line:-1 position:50%
race; gender;
sexual orientation;


32
00:01:14,908 --> 00:01:17,411 line:0
age; abilities; disabilities;


33
00:01:17,411 --> 00:01:19,379 position:50%
whether you are right-
or left-handed;


34
00:01:19,379 --> 00:01:21,114 line:0
body measurements like height;


35
00:01:21,114 --> 00:01:24,284 line:0
and also environmental
conditions like location,


36
00:01:24,284 --> 00:01:28,355 position:50%
internet connectivity,
or access to technology devices.


37
00:01:28,355 --> 00:01:31,458 line:0
Each of these provide
spectrums of perspectives --


38
00:01:31,458 --> 00:01:33,860 position:50%
and even more
unique experiences --


39
00:01:33,860 --> 00:01:35,629 position:50%
when you consider
the intersections


40
00:01:35,629 --> 00:01:39,466 position:50%
of multiple axes
