of your favorite Memories?


639
00:29:23,195 --> 00:29:26,331 line:-1
What Memories did you dislike?


640
00:29:26,331 --> 00:29:29,935 line:-1
What were you feeling
after seeing it?


641
00:29:29,935 --> 00:29:33,472 line:-1
How can we make the experience
better for you?


642
00:29:33,472 --> 00:29:35,641 line:-1
And followed up with things
like, “Why?"


643
00:29:35.641 --> 00:29:37.142 line:-1 position:50%
or "Tell me more about that..."


644
00:29:37,142 --> 00:29:39,878 line:-1
to unpack the answers
even further.


645
00:29:39.878 --> 00:29:42.848 line:-1 position:50%
Formulating the right questions
can be challenging,


646
00:29:42,848 --> 00:29:45,484 line:-1
but it’s a skill
you get better at with practice.


647
00:29:45,484 --> 00:29:48,286 line:-1
If you can,
favor open-ended questions,


648
00:29:48.286 --> 00:29:50.555 line:-1 position:50%
refer to specific moments
in the past


649
00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:54.026 line:-1 position:50%
and avoid using language
that can influence the response.


650
00:29:54.026 --> 00:29:56.795 line:-1 position:50%
Also restrain from bringing
solutions to their problems


651
00:29:56.795 --> 00:29:58.897 line:-1 position:50%
just yet, and take things in.


652
00:29:58.897 --> 00:30:01.433 line:-1 position:50%
By having one-on-one
conversations,


653
00:30:01.433 --> 00:30:04.536 line:-1 position:50%
we were reminded that photos
and videos have the power


654
00:30:04.536 --> 00:30:09.941 line:-1 position:50%
to affect someone's emotions,
both positively and negatively.


655
00:30:09,941 --> 00:30:12,678 line:-1
It can be difficult
to unexpectedly see photos


656
00:30:12,678 --> 00:30:14,546 line:-1
of a loved one who passed away


657
00:30:14,546 --> 00:30:17,282 line:-1
and be reminded
of their absence.


658
00:30:17.282 --> 00:30:19.685 line:-1 position:50%
For others, pictures
of their ex-partner


659
00:30:19.685 --> 00:30:24.022 line:-1 position:50%
can elicit a myriad of emotions,
from sadness to anger.


660
00:30:24.022 --> 00:30:25.757 line:-1 position:50%
And we also learned
that sometimes,


661
00:30:25.757 --> 00:30:28.060 line:-1 position:50%
it's not what is in
the frame that hurts,


662
00:30:28,060 --> 00:30:29,528 line:-1
but the invisible context


663
00:30:29.528 --> 00:30:33.331 line:-1 position:50%
that only the owner of
the photo library knows about.


664
00:30:33,331 --> 00:30:34,633 line:-1
The process of listening


665
00:30:34,633 --> 00:30:38,370 line:-1
and absorbing other people's
experiences can be humbling.


666
00:30:38,370 --> 00:30:40,639 line:-1
It was for me and my team.


667
00:30:40.639 --> 00:30:42.774 line:-1 position:50%
After being immersed
in real stories,


668
00:30:42.774 --> 00:30:46.678 line:-1 position:50%
it is now time to address
the feedback with a new design.


669
00:30:46.678 --> 00:30:49.548 line:-1 position:50%
In our case, to help people
revisit photos and videos


670
00:30:49,548 --> 00:30:50,982 line:-1
that bring joy,


671
00:30:50.982 --> 00:30:53.552 line:-1 position:50%
we thought we'd give them
control over who they see,


672
00:30:53.552 --> 00:30:55.887 line:-1 position:50%
or not,
in Memories.


673
00:30:55,887 --> 00:30:58,890 line:-1
In the first iteration,
we added multiple buttons


674
00:30:58.890 --> 00:31:02.027 line:-1 position:50%
to feature less of a person
while browsing a Memory,


675
00:31:02.027 --> 00:31:03.962 line:-1 position:50%
and we reengineered
our app,


676
00:31:03,962 --> 00:31:06,231 line:-1
so they’ll immediately
see less of these people


677
00:31:06,231 --> 00:31:09,367 line:-1
across the Photos app.


678
00:31:09,367 --> 00:31:12,437 line:-1
For consistency, we looked
at other places in our app


679
00:31:12,437 --> 00:31:15,407 line:-1
where people would want
to affect the experience.


680
00:31:15,407 --> 00:31:18,710 line:-1
We added a Feature Less
action from a Featured photo,


681
00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:20.378 line:-1 position:50%
from the People albums,


682
00:31:20.378 --> 00:31:24.316 line:-1 position:50%
and even from a single asset
while browsing.


683
00:31:24,316 --> 00:31:26,051 line:-1
The next step is to validate


684
00:31:26.051 --> 00:31:29.020 line:-1 position:50%
that a solution
to a problem works.


685
00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:30.922 line:-1 position:50%
As designers and developers,


686
00:31:30.922 --> 00:31:33.792 line:-1 position:50%
the first design we come up with
is our first response


687
00:31:33.792 --> 00:31:36.862 line:-1 position:50%
to the stories we heard
and absorbed.


688
00:31:36.862 --> 00:31:39.064 line:-1 position:50%
However, listening to someone


689
00:31:39,064 --> 00:31:41,399 line:-1
doesn't always mean
we understood them.


690
00:31:41.399 --> 00:31:43.401 line:-1 position:50%
To make sure
you are on the right track


691
00:31:43.401 --> 00:31:44.603 line:-1 position:50%
and solve real problems,


692
00:31:44.603 --> 00:31:48.006 line:-1 position:50%
it is important to circle back
to the people you interviewed,


693
00:31:48,006 --> 00:31:50,776 line:-1
show them your sketches,
and seek their feedback.


694
00:31:50,776 --> 00:31:52,677 line:-1
Is your design
addressing their need?


695
00:31:52.677 --> 00:31:53.712 line:-1 position:50%
And if not,


696
00:31:53,712 --> 00:31:57,382 line:-1
try to understand the nuances
you missed the first time.


697
00:31:57.382 --> 00:31:59.451 line:-1 position:50%
When we showed
our first solution to people,


698
00:31:59.451 --> 00:32:01.486 line:-1 position:50%
we got mixed reactions.


699
00:32:01.486 --> 00:32:05.190 line:-1 position:50%
We learned that we all have
different tolerance thresholds


700
00:32:05.190 --> 00:32:07.893 line:-1 position:50%
and that the action
of featuring less of a person


701
00:32:07,893 --> 00:32:10,662 line:-1
wasn't radical enough for some.


702
00:32:10.662 --> 00:32:12.831 line:-1 position:50%
We took this insight
into account,


703
00:32:12,831 --> 00:32:14,800 line:-1
and in the following
design iteration,


704
00:32:14,800 --> 00:32:18,270 line:-1
left it up to each person
to decide what they would like:


705
00:32:18,270 --> 00:32:21,973 line:-1
feature a person less,
or never feature it again.


706
00:32:21,973 --> 00:32:24,643 line:-1
It might feel evident
in hindsight.


707
00:32:24.643 --> 00:32:27.212 line:-1 position:50%
However, it happens
to all of us.


708
00:32:27,212 --> 00:32:29,147 line:-1
When we get too close
to our products,


709
00:32:29.147 --> 00:32:33.251 line:-1 position:50%
we develop oversights and fail
at meeting people's needs.


710
00:32:33.251 --> 00:32:36.555 line:-1 position:50%
But empathizing with people
can help us course correct


711
00:32:36.555 --> 00:32:39.724 line:-1 position:50%
when we didn't get things
right from the first try.


712
00:32:39.724 --> 00:32:43.328 line:-1 position:50%
Lastly, even details
like glyphs and icons


713
00:32:43.328 --> 00:32:45.931 line:-1 position:50%
can have an impact on people.


714
00:32:45.931 --> 00:32:48.200 line:-1 position:50%
During the final phases
of development,


715
00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:50.535 line:-1 position:50%
we observed that
the thumbs down icon


716
00:32:50,535 --> 00:32:54,206 line:-1
could project a feeling
of disliking the person.


717
00:32:54.206 --> 00:32:56.608 line:-1 position:50%
This might be the case
in some situations


718
00:32:56,608 --> 00:32:57,776 line:-1
but not for others,


719
00:32:57.776 --> 00:33:00.612 line:-1 position:50%
like when a loved one
has passed away.


720
00:33:00,612 --> 00:33:05,650 line:-1
So we decided to use
a more neutral glyph instead.


721
00:33:05.650 --> 00:33:08.720 line:-1 position:50%
So, we just saw through
the example of photo Memories


722
00:33:08.720 --> 00:33:11.289 line:-1 position:50%
that launching a product
is not an end,


723
00:33:11.289 --> 00:33:12.691 line:-1 position:50%
it is a new beginning


724
00:33:12.691 --> 00:33:16.261 line:-1 position:50%
in your design and
development journey.


725
00:33:16,261 --> 00:33:17,662 line:-1
By having inclusion in mind,


726
00:33:17,662 --> 00:33:21,266 line:-1
you will continue to make your
experience better for everyone.


727
00:33:21.266 --> 00:33:25.003 line:-1 position:50%
Remember to first,
look at reviews and feedback


728
00:33:25.003 --> 00:33:28.106 line:-1 position:50%
people using your app or game
left on the Internet,


729
00:33:28,106 --> 00:33:30,709 line:-1
and go the extra mile
to seek feedback from people


730
00:33:30.709 --> 00:33:34.346 line:-1 position:50%
with experiences different
from yours and your friends.


731
00:33:34,346 --> 00:33:36,214 line:-1
Second, empathize


732
00:33:36,214 --> 00:33:38,717 line:-1
and put yourself
in other people's shoes


733
00:33:38.717 --> 00:33:41.186 line:-1 position:50%
by using the many techniques
at your disposal


734
00:33:41,186 --> 00:33:43,788 line:-1
like brainstorming,
working with experts,


735
00:33:43,788 --> 00:33:45,857 line:-1
and individual interviews.


736
00:33:45.857 --> 00:33:47.559 line:-1 position:50%
And finally,
address the feedback


737
00:33:47,559 --> 00:33:51,263 line:-1
even when it’s not your own
experience with the product.


738
00:33:51.263 --> 00:33:54.399 line:-1 position:50%
And remember that sharing back
solutions for validation


739
00:33:54.399 --> 00:33:55.200 line:-1 position:50%
can help ensure


740
00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:59.471 line:-1 position:50%
the experience has actually made
a more positive impact.


741
00:33:59.471 --> 00:34:01.773 line:-1 position:50%
Now back to Caroline.


742
00:34:01.773 --> 00:34:03.575 line:-1 position:50%
Caroline: We hope
the diversity axes


743
00:34:03.575 --> 00:34:06.478 line:-1 position:50%
and the examples we have
shown you today are useful


744
00:34:06,478 --> 00:34:09,881 line:-1
as you tailor an inclusive
design and development process


745
00:34:09,881 --> 00:34:12,217 line:-1
that fits your company
and context.


746
00:34:12,217 --> 00:34:15,453 line:-1
To conclude,
inclusion is a journey.


747
00:34:15.453 --> 00:34:17.589 line:-1 position:50%
Yes, the journey
is sometimes hard,


748
00:34:17.589 --> 00:34:19.991 line:-1 position:50%
but we love solving
hard problems, right?


749
00:34:19.991 --> 00:34:22.794 line:-1 position:50%
Difficulties should only
drive us to try harder


750
00:34:22,794 --> 00:34:25,897 line:-1
to make our apps and games
more inclusive.


751
00:34:25.897 --> 00:34:27.766 line:-1 position:50%
Inclusive design and development


752
00:34:27,766 --> 00:34:30,235 line:-1
stimulates new,
creative solutions.


753
00:34:30.235 --> 00:34:33.505 line:-1 position:50%
Inclusion does not deliver
subpar experiences,


754
00:34:33,505 --> 00:34:35,807 line:-1
but instead opens up
opportunities


755
00:34:35.807 --> 00:34:38.543 line:-1 position:50%
in areas we may have never
considered,


756
00:34:38.543 --> 00:34:41.846 line:-1 position:50%
and offers productive
constraints to narrow our scope


757
00:34:41,846 --> 00:34:44,649 line:-1
and design with more intention.


758
00:34:44,649 --> 00:34:49,254 line:-1
Empowered diverse teams can
deliver more inclusive products.


759
00:34:49.254 --> 00:34:51.723 line:-1 position:50%
Diverse representation
does not guarantee


760
00:34:51.723 --> 00:34:53.959 line:-1 position:50%
inclusivity will come naturally.


761
00:34:53.959 --> 00:34:57.028 line:-1 position:50%
Instead, when people are invited
to share their perspectives,


762
00:34:57,028 --> 00:34:59,931 line:-1
and when perspectives together
impact decisions,


763
00:34:59.931 --> 00:35:02.834 line:-1 position:50%
products can be more inclusive.


764
00:35:02.834 --> 00:35:07.472 line:-1 position:50%
Finally, inclusion must be
infused into the entire design


765
00:35:07.472 --> 00:35:11.309 line:-1 position:50%
and development process --
into empathizing, ideation,


766
00:35:11.309 --> 00:35:16.014 line:-1 position:50%
designing, development,
testing, release, and beyond.


767
00:35:16.014 --> 00:35:18.717 line:-1 position:50%
The examples we shared
demonstrate that inclusion


768
00:35:18.717 --> 00:35:22.854 line:-1 position:50%
is as much of a process as
design and development are,


769
00:35:22,854 --> 00:35:24,723 line:-1
and the resulting
features are better


770
00:35:24,723 --> 00:35:28,493 line:-1
because of the attention
given to inclusion.


771
00:35:28.493 --> 00:35:31.062 line:-1 position:50%
Listening to the lived
experiences of people


772
00:35:31,062 --> 00:35:34,332 line:-1
will help you to understand
the impact of your app or game,


773
00:35:34.332 --> 00:35:37.602 line:-1 position:50%
and to release both innovative
and respectful products


774
00:35:37,602 --> 00:35:38,670 line:-1
in response.


775
00:35:38,670 --> 00:35:42,040 line:-1
Keep the diversity axes
and their intersections in mind


776
00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:44.576 line:-1 position:50%
as you choose
who to focus on.


777
00:35:44.576 --> 00:35:46.011 line:-1 position:50%
We can practice empathy


778
00:35:46.011 --> 00:35:49.247 line:-1 position:50%
and know that inclusive design
is the right thing to do,


779
00:35:49.247 --> 00:35:52.417 line:-1 position:50%
but it’s time to just call this
"good design."


780
00:35:52.417 --> 00:35:54.886 line:-1 position:50%
We can authentically connect
with our audiences


781
00:35:54.886 --> 00:35:56.955 line:-1 position:50%
and learn new perspectives.


782
00:35:56.955 --> 00:35:58.723 line:-1 position:50%
We can handle feedback
with grace


783
00:35:58,723 --> 00:36:02,060 line:-1
and design with them,
rather than for them.


784
00:36:02.060 --> 00:36:03.695 line:-1 position:50%
Let this be day one


785
00:36:03,695 --> 00:36:06,131 line:-1
if you haven’t started
this journey yet.


786
00:36:06.131 --> 00:36:08.066 line:-1 position:50%
You just have to start somewhere


787
00:36:08.066 --> 00:36:10.468 line:-1 position:50%
and try to do
a little more everyday,


788
00:36:10,468 --> 00:36:14,606 line:-1
which helps it become habit
and then the new normal.


789
00:36:14,606 --> 00:36:15,807 line:0
Be sure to check out


790
00:36:15,807 --> 00:36:17,675 line:0
“The practice
of inclusive design”


791
